Polish PPS-43C semi auto pistol ATF approved incl. 2x35rd. magazines.UPC: REDACTED58Caliber: 7.62x25 mm TT Weight: 3.67 kg loaded, 3.04 kg empty Length: 615 Barrel length 250 mm Magazine Capacity 35 roundsEffective range:200 metersThe History...The PPS-43C (Pistolet-Pulemet Sudaeva, model of 1943 = Sudaev SMG) was born as an answer to the need for a weapon that is more compact and mobile than the PPSh-41, then in use by the Soviet Army. The PPSh-41 was somewhat too long to be used by tank crews and mobile recon groups and paratroopers, so late in 1941, the Red Army issued a request for a new more compact sub machine gun (SMG). The designer Sudaev initially designed his new SMG in 1942, and it was adopted under the designation of PPS-42. The next year he refined the design, and this final model was designated as the PPS-43. This model was manufactured in significant numbers (nearly two million PPS-43 weapons were manufactured between 1943 and 1946). The PPS-43 is sometimes referred to as the best SMG of World War II. title: For Trade:  Rare _ Savage Model 99 (.303 savage)
postcontent:
I have a very rare savage model 99B made in 1902 in .303 savage. Serial #227xx, This gun absolutely pristine. Shoots exactly to the point of aim and even have ammo and dies to go with. What makes this gun so rare is the characteristics of a 99B vs. other model 99's is full Octagonal barrel 26" long. Straight grip with a "Perch Belly" Steel rifle butt that is curved, schnoble tip knife edge dovetail. As you can tell in the pictures this gun is beautiful. This gun has never been drilled and tapped..

Model 99b's are rare and in this condition its even more rare. Model 99's used a rotary magazine to hold the cartridges. The rotating magazine uses a spring-loaded spool with grooves to hold the cartridges. It also has a counter to indicate how many shots are left. This guns counter works perfect and functions flawless.

The rotating magazine design allowed the rifle to be one of the first lever-action rifles to use spitzer bullets. Previous lever-action rifles used tubular magazines, which placed cartridges of ammunition end to end. Another safety feature was that upon cocking the rifle, a small pin protrudes above the top receiver to indicate the rifle is cocked and ready to fire. This design was ahead of its time. This is a very early model 99.

This is a great deer rifle or collector piece. This gun will not disappoint. Email or text if interested 918-four02-0854. FTF in tulsa area only.

title: For Sale:  ZASTAVA ARMS OPAP 7.62X39 AK
postcontent:
If you know your Yugo AK's you know this is a good one. This is NOT a WASR or a century put together. This is a like new (maybe 100 rounds fired thru it) Zastava Arms OPAP 7.62x39 AK. The OPAP's are much harder to find and much more desirable than the commonly found NPAP variant. This gun still appears as new finish wise. It does have Yugoslav military furniture. The handguards are M70, the buttstock is from an M76 sniper. The straight comb of the M76 stock eliminates the so called "cheak slap" that is common on the M70 and NPAP variants and positions your head properly on the sights. Not only that, it looks nicer (IMO). This rifle comes with one Yugo bolt hold open 30 round mag (I have many others listed seperately). It also comes with a cleaning rod, original Yugo sling, and 2 muzzle brakes - borth a slant brake and a birdcage brake (both Tapco). This gun is 922r compliant, as it was made for Century at the Zastava arsenal in Yugoslavia (with the exception of the M76 stock which was added). It is matching - except for the M76 buttstock of course. 

First to say they take it, gets it. I do have it cross listed (along with mags, chest rig, ammo, etc.). Trades will not work. The price is $700.
